Dynamic Storage System — User Guide

1. What is Dynamic Storage System?

Dynamic Storage System is an Unreal Engine plugin that lets you store and retrieve runtime data using Gameplay Tags.

Instead of creating many separate variables across different Blueprints or C++ classes, you can save a value with a tag and read it later from another system.

Example idea:

Player.Health → 100
Weapon.CurrentAmmo → 30
Input.MouseLocation → Vector2D
AI.TargetActor → Actor Reference

The plugin works in both Blueprint and C++.


---

2. Main Features

Store data using Gameplay Tags

Retrieve data using Gameplay Tags

Check if data exists

Remove stored data

Works in Blueprint

Works in C++

Type-safe storage and retrieval

Supports common Unreal Engine types

Supports arrays, sets, and maps

Automatically rebuilds Blueprint pin types from stored metadata



---

3. Basic Rule

The type used for retrieval must match the type used for storage.

Correct:

Store Player.Health as int
Get Player.Health as int

Incorrect:

Store Player.Health as int
Get Player.Health as float

If the type does not match, the plugin safely blocks the retrieval and returns a default value.


---

4. Blueprint Usage

The plugin provides four main Blueprint nodes:

Set Storage
Get Storage
Contain Data
Unregister Data


---

4.1 Set Storage

Use Set Storage to save a value.

Steps:

1. Add a Set Storage node.


2. Select a Gameplay Tag.


3. Connect a value to the Value pin.


4. Compile the Blueprint.



Example:

Tag: Player.Health
Value: 100

This stores the integer value 100 under the tag Player.Health.

The Value pin automatically changes to the connected value type.


---

4.2 Get Storage

Use Get Storage to read a value.

Steps:

1. Add a Get Storage node.


2. Select the same Gameplay Tag used in Set Storage.


3. The output pin automatically becomes the correct type.


4. Use the output value normally.



Example:

Tag: Player.Health
Output: int

Important:

Get Storage should use a fixed Gameplay Tag or Make Literal Gameplay Tag.

Dynamic tag variables are not recommended for Get Storage because Blueprint output pins need a known type before compile time.


---

4.3 Contain Data

Use Contain Data to check if a tag currently has stored data.

Example flow:

Contain Data → Branch → Get Storage

This is useful when the value may or may not exist yet.


---

4.4 Unregister Data

Use Unregister Data to remove data from storage.

Example:

Unregister Data: Player.Health

After removal, Contain Data for that tag returns false.


---

5. C++ Implementation

Include the API header:

#include "API/DynamicStorageSystemAPI.h"


---

5.1 Register Data

UDynamicStorageSystemAPI::RegisterData<int32>(
    this,
    FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag(TEXT("Player.Health")),
    100
);


---

5.2 Retrieve Data

int32 Health = UDynamicStorageSystemAPI::RetrieveData<int32>(
    this,
    FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag(TEXT("Player.Health"))
);


---

5.3 Check if Data Exists

bool bExists = UDynamicStorageSystemAPI::ContainsData(
    this,
    FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag(TEXT("Player.Health"))
);


---

5.4 Remove Data

bool bRemoved = UDynamicStorageSystemAPI::UnregisterData(
    this,
    FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag(TEXT("Player.Health"))
);


---

6. Supported Types

The plugin supports common Unreal Engine types.

Basic Types

bool
int32
int64
float
double

Text Types

String
Name
Text

C++ equivalents:

FString
FName
FText

Math Types

Vector
Vector2D
Rotator
Transform

C++ equivalents:

FVector
FVector2D
FRotator
FTransform

Other Supported Types

Enums
Structs
Object references
Class references
Arrays
Sets
Maps

Example container types:

Array<int>
Array<Vector>
Set<string>
Map<Name, int>
Map<String, Vector>
Map<Name, CustomStruct>

Core C++ types (Unsupported by blueprint)
This system also supports c++ core types which are not supported by the blueprints. i.e Non-USTRUCT() structs, Non-UCLASS() classes, NON-UPROPERTY() variables

Note:- The c++ core types does not support the blueprint so the blueprint will not react with these types of data but can be used in c++.

NOTE:- DON'T STORE POINTERS OF BASIC TYPES LIKE INT, FLOAT, BOOL, STRING, NAME, ETC...
NOTE:- ALLOWED POINTERS TYPE VALUES = UOBJECT, CLASS


